content: I guess most of you aleady know what this department will be about
we will analyses famous players games
and try to go through all moves
so that by the end of the lesson we will more or less understand why they played so
and how one could have played better
so that you can become more fmailiar with famous names.

slamduk, tieuphilac, eastmen, Fermat, pantrike, yyfcsd, luwenzhe, killer21st, shuwang, cisco, coco_yuang, FIFAWORLDCUP, bawangwan, virag, tunnet99, dadisheng, weigui, concord2497, Southerner, LiuJianping, forsaken, nick_hopper, smiling, pengyu, mumax, Chancewu, Intotherenju, shaoping.
you are very welcome to be active in these lessons
the more active you are, the more benefit we all get
I chose two very famous players for our first lesson.
the black player is the one time World Champion, Kazuto Hasegawa, 9 dan.
the white player is two times World Champion, Shigeru Nakamura, 9 dan.
the game we will see was played in final match of the japanese championship, in 2001.
This game began with a famous opening of d3.
you have all learned the theory of d3 before.
As you know, there are many playable 5th moves in d3.
this 5 is played a lot in this year email WC
Moves from 6 to 9 are very logical
from here, there are usually two continuations
is it good for white or black?
hehe in rct 4 I use it
maybe balanced... but people say comfortable for black?
black will be safe after long and carefule defence
black has to face some pressure from white
long game, but long game good for white, ?
but a great player such as Hasegawa, of coure he had prepared the black defense here
seems very safe in upper left
especially because he put this 5th move
so, Nakamura probably did not want to play this 10th move that Hasegawa prepared for.
it is important to surprise opponent
and not to be surprised by him
who can be more active in opening choices,
another way is the traditional i7
leading back to the well known theory
sometimes white plays a four at move 14, sometimes not
anyway, Nakamura did not like to repeat too boring patterns
assuming that great Hasegawa has prepared well here
because the variant often occurred in email WC as well as real WC
So Nakamura surprised his opponent with the new 10th move!
had anyone seen that 10th move before?
so it was very interesting for me to watch this game
I was curious, what can Hasegawa, a 9 dan player, do in such new situation.
How can a master make the plan here.
What would you do if you were black here?
black has 2 pairs, and so does white
make its own pair by blocking  one of white's
g11 is too inactive, i think
The g11 has some weakness here
from the good  side - it is good block
the white pair is still alive
black did not gain his own power
and white has the tempo to develop now
now, maybe black is in trouble
maybe white so enough power to win
maybe somebody else wants to try, say me
tunnet just proved, that this 11 loses
its now return to the famous position
lets try some other ways too
any other plans for white here?
12 is not very good maybe? why we play three?
what happened in that famous game then
White took a very strong point
f8 is a very important point for both sides
white took the k10 after that
to give up both f8 and k10
I think, after this 14th move, white had gained the success from the surprise that he planned with move 10
this variant, will be your advancved homework
to prove, whether it is black win or not
He was trying to use positional style
ask hasegawa to do this hw too :)
What amazes me is the situation on the board.
White's pair 10_8 is open all the way
but white doesnt waste it for defense
it would be possible to kill the 7_1
he decided, he can defend without the help of 8_10
and spare the resource, for future use
Nakamurs defended aggressively on the right wing,
Hasegawa just played the simple and best here

claire, tunnet99, tieuphilac, killer21st, Fermat, luwenzhe, pantrike, Southerner, virag, Chancewu, cisco, Volodymyr, Alan, shuwang, slamduk, bawangwan, nick_hopper, coco_yuang, FIFAWORLDCUP, smiling, LiuJianping, shaoping, pengyu, concord2497, Intotherenju, dadisheng, mumax, civsnail, shadewawa, fanx, weigui, fallnavy, yyfcsd.
Who can explain the 22nd move that great Nakamura made?
and gain material for left side
the 22 is a typical inner defense
like i told in tactics lesson
white doesnt always need to fly in the space
but it is enough to stay inside, and cut off the inner support of blacks
Black is using its temorary advantahe and tempo
to fill up the right wing
how about this 24, isnt it same idea as 22?
but now black got f9 indeed
but maybe Nakamura did not think f9 was so needed
he was happy to make sure black structures are all dead
but now, black has fair chances to get draw from this game
of course, true fighter Nakamura was not thinking of draw
now, Hasegawa began to split sides
white does not let black to stretch this wall any longer
what is the idea of this move?
does not allow white to gain space
block white structure and develop attack
yes, good. black is using filling tactics
that is what we learned in the lesson of tempo
and the only weapon left is the tempo
to have time to make useful moves
and the goal is to fill up the lower space
before white gets to do something there
but I guess Mr Hasegawa was reaching time trouble by then
this is a very important factor
which does not show in game records
and makes the readers often wonder
why a master made weak moves
Now, black has filled up the lower space
but with the price of tempo
and we will see, if the remaining upper space is sufficient for white or not
hard to win in Email games.
but one should not waste a three for defense, unless forced
so, black did not play g11
email and face to face games are totally different :)
in real games, the win can happen anytime
most email players would lose easly here but in email maybe yah they get draw)
he took advantage of the structure of 49
for white, its better not to waste the line
now, black became too hopeful about the draw
or was it the time pressure
anyway, Hasegawa played a series of active moves
in order to fill up the upper space
it is a good tactics in time trouble
then you can control the plan
and no need to ponder about the defense
the left wing has become a bit weak for black
but thats the price of forced defence
Hasegawa saved more time on clock by this defense
but weakened a position a bit

black did not have enough time to think of good defense
who wants to show the win?
a great game by two great players,
but always some small factors will determine the result
win in such a narrow space
such as the remaining time on clock
move 67, obviously a move without thinking
we cannot judge the player for that
he just didnt have time for thinking
maybe we can take it back too?)
who will want to try win now?
even you dont see win yet
you can just try and see what happens
there is a 4x4 and tieu missed
maybe a good for medium hw
and then we will have it
